We need to regroup $\purpleD3$ so that the fractional part is **greater** than $\blueD{\dfrac{3}{4}}$.


$\begin{align}
\purpleD3 &=\purpleD{2 + 1} \\\\
&=\purpleD{2} + \purpleD{\dfrac44}\\\\
&=\purpleD{2\dfrac44}
\end{align}$

We can replace $\purpleD3$ with $\purpleD{2} \purpleD{\dfrac{4}{4}}$.

$\begin{align}
&\overset{\purpleD{2}}{\cancel{\purpleD{3}}} &\purpleD{\dfrac{\overset{4}{\cancel{0}}}{4}}\\\\
-&\blueD{1}&\blueD{\dfrac{3}{4}}\\
\hline{}
\end{align}$

Now that the fractions have the same denominator, we can subtract:  

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{\dfrac{9}{18}} - \blueD{\dfrac{2}{18}} &= \dfrac{\maroonD{9} - \blueD{2}}{18}\\
\\
&= \dfrac{7}{18}
\end{align}$
